[Forwarding from the ARL on behalf of six library organizations.  --Peter.]


Contact:
Prudence S. Adler
(202) 296-2296

NEWS for Immediate Release:
American Association of Law Libraries, American=20
Library Association, Association of Research=20
Libraries, Association of College and Research=20
Libraries, Medical Library Association, Special Libraries Association

May 2, 2006

Library Groups Applaud Legislation that Improves=20
Public Access to Federal Scientific Research

Washington, DC=97A coalition of national library=20
associations praised the introduction of the=20
"Federal Research Public Access Act of 2006." The=20
legislation, introduced by Sen. John Cornyn=20
(R-TX) and Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-CT) would=20
require federal agencies with extramural research=20
portfolios over $100 million to make the=20
electronic versions of peer-reviewed articles=20
publicly available via the Internet within 6 months of publication.

"Far too often the results of research that the=20
U.S. government funds=97with billions of taxpayer=20
dollars each year=97are not broadly available to=20
researchers, scientists, physicians and members=20
of the public. This legislation will greatly=20
expand public access while at the same time,=20
ensure that these articles generated with federal=20
support are available to future generations,"=20
said Prudence S. Adler, a spokesperson for the coalition.

Enhanced public access to publicly funded=20
research spurs innovation and competition by=20
accelerating research, sharing knowledge,=20
improving treatment of diseases, and supports the educational enterprise.

The coalition is made up of the American=20
Association of Law Libraries, the American=20
Library Association, the Association of Research=20
Libraries, the Association of College and=20
Research Libraries, the Medical Library=20
Association, and the Special Libraries=20
Association. These associations collectively=20
represent over 139,000 libraries in the United=20
States employing 350,000 librarians and library=20
workers. The mission of libraries is to foster=20
global access to information for creative, research, and educational uses.

The American Association of Law Libraries (AALL)=20
is a nonprofit educational organization with over=20
5,000 members nationwide. AALL's mission is to=20
promote and enhance the value of law libraries to=20
the legal and public communities, to foster the=20
profession of law librarianship, and to provide=20
leadership in the field of legal information and=20
information policy. <http://www.aall.org/>http://www.aall.org/
Contact: Mary Alice Baish (202-662-9200)

The American Library Association (ALA) is a=20
nonprofit educational organization of over 65,000=20
librarians, library trustees, and other friends=20
of libraries dedicated to improving library=20
services and promoting the public interest in a=20
free and open information society. <http://www.ala.org/>http://www.ala.org/
Contact: Miriam Nisbet (202-628-8410)

The Association of Research Libraries (ARL) is a=20
nonprofit organization of 123 research libraries=20
in North America. ARL's members include=20
university libraries, public libraries,=20
government and national libraries. Its mission is=20
to shape and influence forces affecting the=20
future of research libraries in the process of=20
scholarly communication. ARL programs and=20
services promote equitable access to and=20
effective uses of recorded knowledge in support=20
of teaching, research, scholarship and community=20
service. <http://www.arl.org/>http://www.arl.org/
Contact: Prudence S. Adler (202-296-2296)

The Association of College and Research Libraries=20
(ACRL) is a division of the American Library=20
Association (ALA), representing more than 13,000=20
academic and research librarians and interested=20
individuals. Its initiatives enable the higher=20
education community to understand the role that=20
academic libraries play in the teaching,=20
learning, and research environments.=20
<http://www.acrl.org/>http://www.acrl.org/
Contact: Mary Ellen Davis (800-545-24222, x3248)

The Medical Library Association (MLA), a=20
nonprofit, educational organization, is a leading=20
advocate for health sciences information=20
professionals with more than 4,700 members=20
worldwide. Through its programs and services, MLA=20
provides lifelong educational opportunities,=20
supports a knowledgebase of health information=20
research, and works with a global network of=20
partners to promote the importance of quality=20
information for improved health to the health=20
care community and the public.=
 <http://www.mlanet.org/>http://www.mlanet.org/
Contact: Carla Funk (312-419-9094 x14)

The Special Libraries Association (SLA) is a=20
nonprofit global organization for innovative=20
information professionals and their strategic=20
partners. SLA serves more than 12,000 members in=20
83 countries in the information profession,=20
including corporate, academic and government=20
information specialists. SLA promotes and=20
strengthens its members through learning,=20
advocacy and networking initiatives.=
 <http://www.sla.org/>http://www.sla.org/
Contact: Doug Newcomb (703-647-4923)

